summary:
I have always been passionate about computers and fascinated by how machines work. From playing video games to disassembling and reassembling hardware, my hobbies fuelled my passion. I would seek to learn more about computers and physics even before my enrolment in Computer Science at University. That is what sparked my interest in software development.  

My dedication to coding grew even more with time, but I've also discovered other great things on that path: building software with a team, mentoring and solving complex problems. That's how I ended up being CTO of 140 talented developers in Wolox, a fast-growing company. 

After studying my Masters and throughout my career, I have never lost that curiosity to learn and discover, to gain new skills and further develop existing ones.  

Being in a strategic role has also opened my eyes to all of the complex components that make up a company. This sparked new roles for me in sales in San Francisco, and later, a leadership role in Chile. 

After a couple of challenging years in other roles and great adventures with Wolox, I started missing what it was like to build things. That is why I decided it was time to go back to engineering basics, learn what's hot right now and work with passionate like-minded people around the globe.

My past coding adventures include back end development such as Ruby on Rails and NodeJS, as well as complex AWS infrastructures. I'm a fast learner and enthusiastic about researching new technologies and frameworks.

I am currently working in the Authentication and Billing team at WeTransfer, where we develop different solutions for the rest of our suite of products. Some of those solutions included integrating Auth0 for Single Sign On and extracting the billing logic from the main monolithic to a microservice.

I am a crypto enthusiast, so in my free time, I like to read up on the latest news and dive into different decentralised technologies.
